ond »ideas«. The central theme is the way in which Islam was re-constructed as an intellectual and socio-political tradition in Southeast Asia in the nineteen-nineties. Scholars who approach Islam both as a textual and local tradition, students who take the heartlands of Islam as imaginative landscapes for cultural transformation and politicians and institutions which have been concerned with transmitting the idea of »Islamization« are the subjects of this inquiry into different patterns of modernity in a tropical region still bearing the signature of a colonial past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIslamzIndonesiaxHistoriaxSiglo XX. 0aIslamzIndonesiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIslamzMalasiaxHistoriaxSiglo XX. 0aIslamzSingaporexHistoryy20th century. 0aIslamzSingapurxHistoriaxSiglo XX. 0aIslamzalaysiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsia. 4aIslam. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aModernization. 4aPolitics. 4aSociology of Religion. 4aSociology. 4aSoutheast Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aIslam.  aIslamic Studies.  aModernization.  aPolitics.  aSociology of Religion.  aSociology.  aSoutheast Asia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript English Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066155208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Complete Package 2000-2009z9783110463415oZDB-23-TSO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Highlight Collection Sozialw. 2000-2009z9783110463392oZDB-23-TSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839400814zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839400814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co